\subsection{Parametrization}

Typical vibration is conducted with respect to time, particularly since frequency is a time-domaine parameter. Therefore the following parametrization are used:
\begin{equation}
    t =\frac{L}{v} 
\end{equation}

The period of a sinusoidal wave can be expressed as follow:
\begin{equation}
    P = 2*L 
\end{equation}
Therefore to describe the applied change of height occuring, it can be denoted by the following y(t) function:
\begin{equation}
    y(t)=A\sin{(2*v*t)}
\end{equation}

Where y(t) is a piecewise function given by 
\begin{equation}
    \begin{cases} 
        0 & t_i < 0 \\
        y(t)=A\sin{(2*v*t)} & t_i<t<t_f \\ 
        0 & t_f > \frac{L}{V}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}

As such we have characterized in the time domain the events to be considered. 

